metadata.name: Acequia #125
metadata.description:
Acequia (“ah-seh-kee-uh”) - a Spanish adaptation of the Arabic word as-sāqiya, meaning “water carrier”. 

In our second collaboration, Rich and Rick are back with our blend of generative code, intricate design, attention to detail, and a splash of charm. 

 Acequias are traditional irrigation canals used to distribute rainwater and snowmelt along a complex network of narrow channels. They are found in Spain, the American Southwest, and northern Mexico, where they are essential for sustaining fields, orchards, and gardens in semi-arid regions.   
Our aim in this series is to capture the essence of these waterways in bold geometric designs. Each piece is inspired by a mountain village or town in Andalusia (southern Spain). 

The location determines the cube designs and construction rules that are used to build the final output. These are combined with striking day/night palettes, outline styles, scales, climates, and a few surprises of course!


Controls (in live view): 

- Press [p] to pause water animation 
- Press [e] to complete water animation 
- Press [r] to reset water animation 
- Press [s] to save the current image 
- Press [h] for a high-res output suitable for printing 
- Press [b] to toggle the border

metadata.name: Mandala #12
metadata.description:
A mandala is a geometric configuration of symbols.
With the help of vectors, the symmetrical geometric shapes of the mandala automatically attract the attention of the person to the center of the circle.
Most artists today draw mandalas without circles and squares, which is amazing from an aesthetic standpoint, but an original mandala with the characteristics that are present in the historical and ancient definitions will definitely have circles and squares.
Mandalas are seen by Carl Jung as archetypes of the self, symbols of wholeness and order, which are used to organize and rearrange chaos.
The mandala design is a way to relieve tension and focus the mind.
Mandalas are used in art therapy to help patients gain mastery over their minds and achieve peace, also Mandala establishes a new connection between the conscious and the unconscious.
This old pattern throws out internal issues and acts as a projection device.

Everyone in the world has their own mandala that can be formed in their paintings and artistic activities.

metadata.name: Rotation of Distortion #6
metadata.description:
There are two remarkable aspects to this algorithm, the first is how it distorts and arranges lines next to each other, and the second is how it rotates them.
The combination of rotation and distortion produces special shapes, in some of which combination of lines distorted; in others, lines are rotated around a particular point. Some outputs, however, benefit from both of these equally and as a result produce an output that is more visually appealing.
There is only one color palette used in each output containing four colors in order to prevent confusion caused by the interference of colors.
Made by p5.js

press 's' to save original size (3508 x 4961)

metadata.name: BINARY WORDS #45
metadata.description:
I drew my first 8x8 pixel binary image on 11/08/2022 with 'iloveyou' encoded for my wife, it was our 10-year anniversary on this day.  After that made this generative stuff for fxhash's birthday bash.

#fxhashturnsone

Donations:
25% to ThreeJs team

The image contains a binary coded word or phrase with a length of 8 characters. The grays represents 0, the other colors represents 1. One row -> one character. Should be proceed decoding from left to right and from top to bottom.

An example: 'iloveyou'

01101001
01101100
01101111
01110110
01100101
01111001
01101111
01110101

The fxrandom selects a word and the program converts it to binary data. After that, the background (ground and sky) is randomly generated from color schemes. Then the binary gray colors are drawn. Also the color of light next to null colors is randomly generated from color schemes. Random affects also the animation.

The animation stops when you do these interactions below, then restarts after a few seconds of inactivity.

Press spacebar to change:

- frame view -> without frame
- without frame -> original 8x8px size
- original 8x8px size -> frame view

Press 's' to save an svg from current view.

Notes:
- Build with ReactJs and TweenJs
- Every upcoming day, half of the remaining pieces are burned.

Happy Birthday fxhash community!
I'm glad to be among you!

metadata.name: Agharta #51
metadata.description:
It may appear as an indecipherable map to some. To others, it may present itself as a cross section of an underground cave. Or maybe an uncanny landscape of volcanic activity, a diagram of geological strata, or even something else entirely. Some vague structure may also appear; is it the remains of an ancient civilization? Or perhaps a glimpse into our own tomorrow?

In "Agharta", I sought to create a generative work that could invite the viewer to explore the depths of their imagination and uncover hidden structures within the seemingly chaotic composition. The idea came to me when I was exploring Simplex noise and pixel displacement in Cables. I was surprised by the emergent structures that appeared when some set of parameters paired with the right texture. 

The title of the piece references the mythical underground world said to be located at the earth's core. This idea of hidden depths and secret worlds within the earth resonates with the abstract and enigmatic nature of the result generated by the noise. Imagery of landscape, vague structures, or geological features may appear but never stand out on its own; it exists in a state of constant flow and intersection as if viewed from another dimension. And just like the myth itself that bring up numerous theories that doesn’t necessarily connected to each other, it hints at that idea of an elusive imagined realm while never actually represent it completely.



=========

Controls:

[1] Set resolution to 716 x 1024px (default)

[2] Set resolution to 1433 x 2048px

[3] Set resolution to 2688 x 3840px

* The presets above are suitable for screen viewing up to 4k screen resolution. To set a custom resolution for printing and other purpose, add &res=[desired resolution] at the end of the URL. It will set the height of the image, and the width will be calculated automatically at 0.7 ratio. For example to get a resolution of 4911 x 7016px (about the size of A2 paper), add &res=7016 as URL parameter.

[Scroll/pinch] to zoom and drag to pan

[r] or [zoom out to max] Reset position

[c] Capture a screenshot of the current state at rendered resolution


Notes:

* This project use shaders that relies on GPU. Hi-res output may slow down your device. Since it also utilize GPU instance for thumbnail rendering, expect longer time for every iterations to be signed by fx(hash).

* If 'glitching' occurs or the composition behaves differently at different resolution, just refresh the page to reset it (except for the thin lines, which are always drawn at approximately 1 pixel, so expect it to vary at different resolution).

Made with cables.gl, a node-based webgl environment

XALTED 2022

metadata.name: Digital Surrogates #113
metadata.description:
“Allan McCollum’s Plaster Surrogates was a thought-provoking series of sculptures that examines the role of art in contemporary society. The sculptures are cast from plaster and painted to resemble frames, mats, and black rectangles, creating a visual illusion of empty picture frames. McCollum's intention with the surrogates was to comment on the mass production and consumption of art objects, as well as the way in which art is often valued for its social function rather than its inherent aesthetic qualities.”

Continuing the integration of generative art and conceptual art, this work is a digital reproduction and inspiration of Plaster Surrogates - 1982 by noted conceptual artist, Allan McCollum.

Even though the original work had completely black rectangles, in this work, contrasting colors are used in some variations to increase the beauty. The dimensions and colors of the frames are calculated according to McCollum's original work. Various color palettes and canvas sizes have been used.

-----------

No images are used, created entirely by coding. Textures such as wood, canvas, and oil paint have been created to create a realistic look. Preview optimized for fxhash capturing system and full rendering can take up to several minutes, so I highly recommend checking out this artwork in high quality.


To save the artwork in high resolution, Open it in the live mode, it will be saved automatically after completion.

Made with p5js.
